     283                 :            :   // InnerMap is a generic hash-based map.  It doesn't contain any
     284                 :            :   // protocol-buffer-specific logic.  It is a chaining hash map with the
     285                 :            :   // additional feature that some buckets can be converted to use an ordered
     286                 :            :   // container.  This ensures O(lg n) bounds on find, insert, and erase, while
     287                 :            :   // avoiding the overheads of ordered containers most of the time.
     288                 :            :   //
     289                 :            :   // The implementation doesn't need the full generality of unordered_map,
     290                 :            :   // and it doesn't have it.  More bells and whistles can be added as needed.
     291                 :            :   // Some implementation details:
     292                 :            :   // 1. The hash function has type hasher and the equality function
     293                 :            :   //    equal_to<Key>.  We inherit from hasher to save space
     294                 :            :   //    (empty-base-class optimization).
     295                 :            :   // 2. The number of buckets is a power of two.
     296                 :            :   // 3. Buckets are converted to trees in pairs: if we convert bucket b then
     297                 :            :   //    buckets b and b^1 will share a tree.  Invariant: buckets b and b^1 have
     298                 :            :   //    the same non-NULL value iff they are sharing a tree.  (An alternative
     299                 :            :   //    implementation strategy would be to have a tag bit per bucket.)

     301                 :            :   //    stored in linked list nodes.  Pointers to elements are never invalidated
     302                 :            :   //    until the element is deleted.
